y or partly in Suffolk: Ipswich Hospital NHS Trust, West Suffolk Hospital NHS Foundation Trust, Norfolk and Suffolk NHS Foundation Trust, East of England Ambulance Service NHS Trust</p><p> </p><p>Employers across the NHS are responsible for protecting their staff. The Government is committed to helping trusts discharge their obligations to keep their staff safe through its manifesto commitment that it “will take vigorous and immediate action against those who abuse or attack the people who work for and make our NHS” and strengthening legislation.</p><p>The Department is working with NHS Improvement and NHS England on plans for new central support arrangements to help trusts tackle assaults and abuse of their staff including a new data collection.</p><p>The Department also announced that paramedics will be given body cameras to protect them from abuse. This scheme will be piloted in North East and South East Coast Ambulance Services before being rolled out.</p><p>The Assaults on Emergency Workers (Offences) Bill 2017-19 will become law imminently meaning tougher sentences can be handed down against those who attack and abuse public services staff including NHS staff in the course of their duties.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","169282","2018-09-11T16:01:38.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964468/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964468/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964468/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-09-03","NHS: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many assaults there have been on NHS staff in Suffolk in each year since 2009.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Dan Poulter","169283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964469","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-09-06","<p>‘Health and Harmony: the future for food, farming and the environment in a Green Brexit’ published in February 2018 set out a clear direction of travel for future farm support in England. This consultation paper proposed a new system of paying farmers and land managers ‘public money for public goods’. The consultation closed in May and we intend to bring forward an Agriculture Bill shortly.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-09-06T12:06:33.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964469/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964469/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964469/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-09-03","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress the Government has made on plans for farming subsidies after Britain leaves the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Dan Poulter","169284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964470","Department for International Development","false","2018-09-10","<p>DFID is committed to taking a comprehensive approach to mental health.</p><p> </p><p>Through the Disability Rights Fund, we support organisations led by people with psychosocial disabilities to champion their rights. In Ghana, our Health Sector Support Programme has supported mental health systems strengthening and efforts to address underlying stigma and discrimination. And we are generating world-leading evidence around integrating effective mental health care services into primary care through PRIME - our Programme for Improving Mental Health Care.</p><p> </p><p>DFID will set out its future approach on global mental health in our upcoming Disability Framework, following the UK-hosted Global Ministerial Mental Health Summit this October.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-09-10T16:41:01.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964470/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964470/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964470/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-09-03","Developing Countries: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to improve mental health globally.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Dan Poulter","169285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964471","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-09-13","<p>On 23 July we announced that the next auction in the Contract for Difference support scheme for renewable electricity generation will open by May next year, and that we plan to set out the parameters of the auction later this year. I also announced our intention to run subsequent auctions around every two years after that.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-09-13T15:20:45.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964471/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964471/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964471/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-09-03","Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans his Department has to support the development of renewable energy schemes.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Dan Poulter","169286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964472","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-09-17","<p>Great Britain currently has 3GW of interconnection capacity to continental Europe, via links to France and the Netherlands.</p><p>There is 4.4GW of new interconnector capacity under construction, which will increase our capacity to France and add connections to Belgium and Norway. In addition, there are further projects that have been given regulatory approval or are in the process of applying for regulatory approval, which could add another 9GW of capacity, but these are at an earlier stage of development.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-09-17T13:18:26.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964472/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964472/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964472/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-09-03","Electricity Interconnectors: Europe","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans his Department has to develop electricity grid connections with countries in continental Europe.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Dan Poulter","169287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964473","Department for Transport","false","2018-09-11","<p>Greater Anglia has a Franchise Agreement commitment to restore a direct train service between Lowestoft and London Liverpool Street via Ipswich. In line with this commitment, Greater Anglia are currently working with industry partners to secure the necessary access rights and approvals to secure the delivery of this direct service.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-09-11T15:20:39.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964473/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964473/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964473/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-09-03","Railways: Suffolk","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans his Department has for restoring a direct train service between Lowestoft and London Victoria via Ipswich.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr Dan Poulter","169288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964474","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-09-11","<p>Information collated by NHS England in 2017 indicates that around half of hospital trusts were delivering patient education and support events for breast cancer patients. However, it is important to note that in the same information collection, almost all trusts indicated they are providing health and wellbeing information and support through various methods, including one-to-one conversations. Additionally, the recovery package, a set of four interventions designed to help patients and clinicians assess a patient’s holistic needs and plan appropriately for their care and support, is being commissioned and delivered in full or in part by many clinical commissioning groups and providers across England.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-09-11T13:42:35.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964474/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964474/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964474/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-09-03","Breast Cancer: Health Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many hospital trusts are providing access to a patient education and support event for breast cancer patients.","false","Biography information for Karen Lee","Lincoln","Karen Lee","169848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964475","Department for Transport","false","2018-09-11","<p>The Department for Transport does not hold information on the number of claims made against local authorities for pothole damages, or the cost of successful claims to the public purse. The matter of insurance and dealing with any compensation claims due to possible defects, including potholes, on the local highway network, is a matter for the relevant local highway authority. Local highway authorities have a delegated statutory responsibility for managing and maintaining their roads as set out in the Highways Act 1980 (as amended).</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-09-11T14:31:00.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964475/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964475/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964475/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-09-03","Roads: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many claims have been made against local authorities for pothole damage; and what the cost to the public purse was of successful claims in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Laura Smith","Crewe and Nantwich","Laura Smith","169790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964476","Treasury","false","2018-09-10","<p>Individuals in receipt of the higher rate mobility component of Disability Living Allowance (DLA) and its successor, Personal Independence Payment (PIP) qualify for an exemption from Vehicle Excise Duty (VED). A fifty per cent reduction in VED is available to those in receipt of the PIP standard rate mobility component.</p><p> </p><p>Individuals who do not qualify for an exemption or the reduced rate pay VED in line with other motorists. To limit the impact on the public finances, a five per cent surcharge applies to monthly and six monthly direct debit payments.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick","169750","2018-09-10T14:28:45.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964476/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964476/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964476/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-03","Excise Duties: Motor Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Government provides support for the payment of vehicle excise duty to people in receipt of welfare.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","169749"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964477","Treasury","false","2018-09-10","<p>Individuals in receipt of the higher rate mobility component of Disability Living Allowance (DLA) and its successor, Personal Independence Payment (PIP) qualify for an exemption from Vehicle Excise Duty (VED). A fifty per cent reduction in VED is available to those in receipt of the PIP standard rate mobility component.</p><p> </p><p>Individuals who do not qualify for an exemption or the reduced rate pay VED in line with other motorists. To limit the impact on the public finances, a five per cent surcharge applies to monthly and six monthly direct debit payments.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick","169749","2018-09-10T14:28:45.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964477/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964477/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964477/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-03","Excise Duties: Motor Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of waiving the surcharge for paying road tax on a monthly basis for people in receipt of welfare benefits.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","169750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964478","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-09-11","<p>The information requested is not centrally held.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-09-11T13:55:03.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964478/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964478/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964478/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-09-03","Respite Care: Hospital Beds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate he has made on the number of adult social care respite beds provided by local authorities in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Laura Smith","Crewe and Nantwich","Laura Smith","169791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964479","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-09-06","<p>The Foreign Secretary spoke to Saudi Foreign Minister Al-Jubeir on 16 August and urged a quick and transparent investigation. I also spoke to the Saudi Foreign Minister on 4 September.</p><p>On 1 September, the Coalition announced the outcome of this investigation, their regret and action to address the recommendations of that investigation. We welcome this acknowledgement and these steps.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-09-06T15:49:07.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964479/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964479/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964479/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-09-03","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the Saudi Arabian Government on the Saudi-led coalition attack on a bus in Saada, Yemen on 9 August 2018.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","169636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964480","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-09-06","<p>The recent report from the Group of Eminent Experts further underlines the deeply concerning human rights situation in Yemen and the importance of reaching a political solution to this conflict. We are carefully considering the contents of the report ahead of the upcoming session of the UN Human Rights Council.</p><p>As we have consistently, we will continue to emphasise to all members of the Coalition the vital importance of compliance with international humanitarian law, press for action to address the humanitarian crisis, and encourage all parties to engage in the UN-led political process in good faith.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-09-06T15:50:52.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964480/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964480/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964480/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-09-03","Yemen: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the Government plans to support the renewal of the mandate of the group of eminent experts on Yemen at the forthcoming UN Human Rights Council meeting.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","169637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964481","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-09-11","<p>The Government response to the Internet Safety Strategy consultation, published in May 2018, announced our intention to publish a joint DCMS-Home Office White Paper to set out more definitive steps on online harms and safety.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the Government response, we published a draft version of our social media code of practice. As required by the Digital Economy Act 2017, we are now consulting with social media providers and others on the code. We will set out further information relating to the code as part of our forthcoming White Paper.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","169548","2018-09-11T10:36:30.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964481/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964481/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964481/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-09-03","Digital Economy Act 2017","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what the timeframe is for section 103 of the Digital Economy Act 2017 to come into force.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","169543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964482","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-09-11","<p>​I refer the Hon. Member to answer of 11 July 2018 (PQ 160284).</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-09-11T14:08:36.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964482/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964482/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964482/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-09-03","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to improve the transparency of its Official Development Assistance after the publication of the Aid Transparency Index 2018.","false","Biography information for Jo Swinson","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson","169155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964483","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-09-11","<p>The UN Verification and Inspection Mechanism (UNVIM) facilitates commercial imports into Yemen's Red Sea ports of Hodeidah and Saleef, and is an important mechanism taking into account the arms embargo enacted by UN Security Council Resolution 2216. UNVIM only applies to commercial vessels.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-09-11T15:30:32.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964483/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964483/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964483/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-09-03","Yemen: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the effect of the UN Verification and Inspection Mechanism for Yemen on the time taken for humanitarian aid to reach Hodeidah port.","false","Biography information for Jo Swinson","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson","169156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964484","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-09-11","<p>​The UK is providing £1.3 million this financial year to the UN's Verification and Inspection Mechanism (UNVIM) to facilitate commercial shipping and assure the Coalition that weapons are not coming into Yemen on large commercial ships docking at Red Sea ports. We have also deployed UK maritime experts to Djibouti to further boost the inspections process, increasing the proportion of ships physically inspected more than ten-fold (from 8 per cent to 90 per cent).</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-09-11T15:32:07.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964484/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964484/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964484/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-09-03","Yemen: International Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to support improvements in the efficiency of the UN Verification and Inspection Mechanism for Yemen.","false","Biography information for Jo Swinson","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson","169157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964485","Department for International Development","false","2018-09-10","<p>DFID has been providing support to all UK Government Departments that spend aid funds to achieve a good or very good rating in the Aid Transparency Index by 2020. This includes formal training days, policy advice, technical guidance and tailored advice.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-09-10T16:39:42.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964485/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964485/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964485/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-09-03","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to help the Foreign and Commonwealth Office to achieving a good or very good rating for the transparency of its aid spending by 2020.","false","Biography information for Jo Swinson","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson","169158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964486","Department for International Development","false","2018-09-10","<p>The UK government is providing £1.3 million in funding to the UN Verification and Inspection Mechanism (UNVIM) this financial year to facilitate commercial imports into Hodeidah and Saleef ports by giving the coalition confidence that weapons are not coming in on large commercial ships. We have also deployed UK maritime experts to Djibouti to help further boost the inspections process, increasing the proportion of physical inspections by more than ten-fold.</p><p> </p><p>The UK continues to urge all parties to the conflict to facilitate full and unhindered access for humanitarian and commercial supplies, such as food, medicine and fuel, through Hodeidah port.</p><p> </p><p>Hodeidah port currently remains open and we are closely monitoring imports through it. In August, Hodeidah accounted for 64% of total bulk food imports and 54% of total fuel imports into Yemen.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-09-10T17:06:31.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964486/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964486/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964486/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-09-03","Yemen: Ports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent steps her Department has taken to help increase the amount of food, medicine and fuel arriving at Hodeidah port.","false","Biography information for Jo Swinson","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson","169159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964487","Home Office","false","2018-09-06","<p>The most recent assessment of the adequacy of the asylum support rates is set out in a report published in March 2018, which can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/report-on-review-of-cash-allowance-paid-to-asylum-seekers" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/report-on-review-of-cash-allowance-paid-to-asylum-seekers</a>.</p><p>We are currently undertaking a further review of the rates and have consulted key stakeholders in the normal way.</p><p>The consultation period has now ended and a decision on whether the rates should change will be made shortly.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-09-06T15:30:16.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964487/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964487/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964487/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-09-03","Asylum: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment his Department has made of the adequacy of the rates of financial assistance provided through asylum support.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","169325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964488","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-09-11","<p>​The Foreign Secretary spoke to Saudi Foreign Minister Al-Jubeir on 16 August and urged a quick and transparent investigation. On 1 September, the Saudi-led Coalition's Joint Incidents Assessment Team announced the outcome of an investigation into the 9 August incident, its regret and action to address the recommendations of that investigation. We welcome this acknowledgement and these steps.</p><p>I spoke to Emirati Deputy Foreign Minister, Dr Gargash, and to Saudi Foreign Minister Al-Jubeir about these matters further on 3 and 4 September respectively. The Saudi Foreign Minister confirmed that the Coalition would implement the recommendations of that investigation.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-09-11T15:45:11.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964488/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964488/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964488/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-09-03","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has has with his counterparts in the Saudi-Emirati-led coalition on military operations in Saada on 9 August.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","169724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964489","Home Office","false","2018-09-11","<p>Newly recognised refugees can continue to claim asylum support for a further 28 days after the grant of their status. There are no plans to extend this period.</p><p>The grant of refugee status means refugees are eligible to apply for mainstream benefits. If they would like assistance with the application an early appointment at a local job centre is arranged for them. This process is designed to ensure that refugees receive the first payment of any benefit they are entitled to before the 28 days period expires, either by full payment of the benefit or through an advance payment.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-09-11T12:55:59.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964489/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964489/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964489/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-09-03","Asylum: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether he has plans to extend the length of time that newly recognised refugees can continue to claim asylum support after a decision to grant leave to remain.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","169326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964490","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-09-11","<p>​On 1 September, the Saudi-led Coalition's Joint Incidents Assessment Team announced the outcome of an investigation into the 9 August incident, its regret and action to address the recommendations of that investigation. We welcome this acknowledgement and these steps.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-09-11T15:46:14.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964490/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964490/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964490/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-09-03","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of whether the attack on Saada, Yemen on 9 August was a legitimate military operation in line with international humanitarian law.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","169725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964491","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-09-11","<p>​The recent report from the Group of Eminent Experts further underlines the deeply concerning human rights situation in Yemen and the importance of reaching a political solution to this conflict. We are carefully considering the contents of the report ahead of the upcoming session of the UN Human Rights Council.</p><p>As we have consistently, we will emphasise to all parties the vital importance of compliance with international humanitarian law, press for action to address the humanitarian crisis, and encourage all parties to engage in the UN-led political process in good faith.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-09-11T15:47:19.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964491/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964491/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964491/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-09-03","Yemen: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the Government plans to support the renewal of the mandate of the group of eminent experts on Yemen at the UN Human Rights Council meeting in September.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","169726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964492","Home Office","false","2018-09-11","<p>All asylum interviews are carried out by an impartial interviewing officer.</p><p>All interpreters engaged by the Home Office must demonstrate they have the required skills and qualifications. They must also:</p><ul><li>be a full member of the National Register of Public Services Interpreters (NRPSI), or</li><li>hold a Diploma in Public Services Interpreting (DPSI) (Law) or a letter of Credit in all oral components (Law), or</li><li>have been assessed by the Asylum and Immigration Tribunal (AIT) (formerly the Immigration Appellate Authority), or</li><li>have been assessed by the Metropolitan Police.</li></ul><p>They are also bound by a “Code of Conduct” to ensure minimum standards for interpreting and behaviour.</p><p>Home Office policy and guidance ensures that in the event of interpreters or interviews falling short of those standards, it would not adversely affect an individual’s asylum claim.</p><p>Interviewing Officers are encouraged to provide feedback on the performance of interpreters, using specifically designed monitoring forms. Interviews may also be monitored for training and security purposes.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-09-11T12:15:49.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964492/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964492/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964492/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-09-03","Asylum: Interpreters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what measures are in place to ensure that interpreters of interviews during the asylum process are able to translate to a high quality and produce work to an accredited standard.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","169327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964493","Home Office","false","2018-09-11","<p>The Home Office has provided grant-funding on a national level to Migrant Help for the provision of independent advice to asylum seekers since April 2014.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-09-11T12:49:45.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964493/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964493/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964493/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-09-03","Asylum: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether his Department has plans to fund independent advice on the asylum process for people subject to asylum processes.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","169328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964494","Home Office","false","2018-09-11","<p>All asylum claimants have the opportunity to be legally represented during the consideration of their asylum claim; the Legal Aid Agency ensures that legal aid funding is provided to those who need it. Free independent guidance is available to claimants provided by Migrant Help, including on finding legal representation. The straightforward nature of the screening interview means that claimants do not, in general, need to have legal advice prior to that interview.</p><p>The process of making an asylum decision is underpinned by an overall assessment of credibility where decision-makers must carefully consider all available evidence, including responses and statements provided during the completion of the screening questionnaire. Where a claimant makes a statement at asylum screening which is inconsistent with a statement provided later, they will be provided an opportunity to explain the discrepancy during their substantive interview.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-09-11T12:43:22.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964494/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964494/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964494/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-09-03","Asylum: Interviews","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether he has plans to ensure that (a) people seeking asylum are able to access legal advice prior to their screening interviews and (b) screening interviews for asylum are not used during credibility assessments.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","169329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964495","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-09-11","<p>The General Data Protection Regulation came into force in May 2018. It is too soon to make a meaningful assessment of the impact to the public purse of Subject Access Requests to general practitioners.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-09-11T16:18:11.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964495/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964495/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964495/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-09-03","General Practitioners: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of Subject Access Requests to GPs in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","169338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964496","Treasury","false","2018-09-11","<p>HMRC do not record the number of requests made using the form 07/18. HMRC do not differentiate between Employment History requests made using the HMRC form 07/18 and the requests received using other methods, for example customer letters and verbal requests. HMRC is therefore unable to provide the information requested.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC may also receive requests for Employment Histories using this form for customers suffering from mesothelioma. These customers cases are treated as urgent due to the nature of the illness and the HMRC target is to reply to these in 10 working days.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-09-11T10:12:44.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964496/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964496/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964496/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-09-03","Revenue and Customs: Forms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the average time taken was HMRC to produce proof of employment history for applicants using form HMRC 07/18; what performance targets have been set for HMRC for the production of that evidence; and how many and what proportion of applications did not meet those targets.","false","Biography information for Martin Whitfield","East Lothian","Martin Whitfield","169735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964497","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-09-11","<p>No assessment has been made by the Department.</p><p>Universal Credit allows Work Coaches to tailor conditionality, setting requirements based on what is reasonable in the individual’s circumstances. Where a claimant is experiencing domestic abuse, in discussion with the Work Coach, requirements can be tailored and in some circumstances switched off for an agreed period of time.</p><p>There are circumstances when a claimant’s work search and availability requirements must be switched off for an agreed period of time, and other work-related requirements can be lifted too where appropriate. This includes where the claimant has suffered domestic violence and abuse, or periods where a child in their care is suffering distress due to experiencing or witnessing violence or abuse.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2018-09-11T11:31:42.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964497/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964497/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964497/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-09-03","Universal Credit: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment her Department has made of the adequacy of easements in benefit conditionality for claimants of universal credit experiencing domestic abuse.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","169330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964498","Cabinet Office","false","2018-09-06","<p>The recruitment process for the role of Government Chief Security Officer is ongoing.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-09-06T16:39:24.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964498/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964498/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964498/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-09-03","Government Chief Security Officer: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the post of Government Chief Security Officer has been filled; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","169860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964499","Department for Education","false","2018-09-11","<p>The department engages regularly with the sector on policy for care leavers, including on Staying Put and funding for the scheme.</p><p>The strategy for care leavers, ‘Keep on Caring’, was published in July 2016. It confirmed that new burdens funding would continue to be paid to local authorities through to the end of this Parliament, using the amount allocated in the period 2016 to 2017 of £22.2 million as the baseline, up-rated each year by 2% to take account of inflation.</p><p>In the period 2017 to 2018, a further £22.85m was provided. This increased to £23.3 million in the period 2018 to 2019. This will increase again to £23.77 million in the period 2019 to 2020. Funding beyond March 2020 will be subject to the outcome of future Spending Reviews.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-09-11T15:47:34.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964499/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964499/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964499/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-09-03","Care Leavers: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of the level of funding for the staying put policy.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","169010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964500","Cabinet Office","false","2019-01-30","<p>The government is committed to reducing the unnecessary duplication of data across the public sector. The General Data Protection Regulation and Data Protection Act came into effect in the UK in 2018 and enshrines key principles of purpose limitation and data minimisation in the processing of personal data. The government will publish in due course a National Data Strategy which will set out specific measures to improve government's approach to the handling and use of data.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2019-01-30T14:22:03.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964500/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964500/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964500/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-09-03","Government: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what measures are in place to reduce the possession of duplicated citizens data across Government.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","169861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964502","Cabinet Office","false","2018-09-06","<p>At 31st of July 2018, the Government Digital Service employed 740 Civil Servants. Included in that figure are seventeen summer interns.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-09-06T16:17:55.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964502/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964502/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964502/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-09-03","Government Digital Service: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people are employed by the Government Digital Service.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","169863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964503","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-09-11","<p>The level of funding for products undergoing review by NHS England will be determined during the 2019/20 planning process.</p><p> </p><p>In 2016/17 and 2017/18, £25 million was set aside for discretionary investment in new specialised services. This was determined by NHS England, who considered it an appropriate level of investment in the context of NHS England’s Specialised Commissioning functioning having to achieve overall efficiency savings of approximately 2.5% and 2.7% in 2016/17 and 2017/18 respectively in order to meet the financial pressures resulting from demographic growth and the legal requirement to fund all positive National Institute for Health and Care Excellence technology appraisals.</p><p> </p><p>The split in the overall funding available between the November and May prioritisation rounds is not fixed but determined each year based on the number and estimated cost of treatments being considered by the independently chaired Clinical Priorities Advisory Group (CPAG) in each round. Revealing the split risks revealing commercial in confidence information around pricing. Anything that is not prioritised in the November round has the opportunity to be considered at the May round therefore ensuring consideration against the full funding envelope for the financial year.</p><p> </p><p>Where manufacturers have requested the cover sheets of the policy propositions, they have received the CPAG summary report as presented at the May 2018 meeting from NHS England.</p><p> </p><p>The full scoring methodology that is used at all prioritisation meetings is published on the NHS England website. This can be found at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/wp-content/uploads/sites/12/2016/06/prioritisation-method-cons-response.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/wp-content/uploads/sites/12/2016/06/prioritisation-method-cons-response.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The outcome of the May 2018 prioritisation process through use of this methodology has been published as a ranked list of five prioritisation Levels. This can be found at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/2017/12/nhs-england-announces-new-specialised-treatments-for-patients/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/2017/12/nhs-england-announces-new-specialised-treatments-for-patients/</a></p><p> </p><p>The impact assessments for all the treatments include a narrative about the estimated forecast financial implications for each item, based on the list price. These are published as part of the public consultation pack. The detailed costings are not shared as in many cases these are based on discount prices provided on a commercial in confidence basis.</p><p> </p><p>The methodology for relative prioritisation has been subject to legal advice as part of its development and implementation, and NHS England believes it complies with equalities legislation, the NHS Constitution and human rights legislation.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England routinely publishes the stakeholder engagement response report as part of consultation through policy development, but does not routinely publish any responses that arise as a result of public consultation.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has no plans to introduce a revised decision-making process for ultra-orphan medicines as introduced in Scotland following the Montgomery Review. NHS England will continue to use the methodology for prioritisation that has previously been publicly consulted on.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","169110 ; 169111 ; 169112 ; 169113 ; 169114 ; 169115 ; 169116 ; 169117 ; 169118","2018-09-11T16:26:10.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964503/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964503/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/964503/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-09-03","Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what funding his Department plans to allocate to products undergoing review by the NHS England relative prioritisation process in 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Mark Tami","Alyn and Deeside","Mark Tami","169109"
